Slide 2
“Let me start with the key message.
When AI gives us a weak output, it’s usually not just a tool issue. A lot of the time, it comes from how we brief the tool.
If the prompt is vague, the output will probably need more review, more corrections and therefore  more work.

That’s why having a simple prompt standard matters: it helps us get better first drafts, faster, and reduces rework.

Today I’ll focus on one practical structure we can use for day-to-day requests: R + T + C + O — Role, Task, Context, and Output.”

Slide 3
“Why does this matter?
What we want from AI is not only a faster answer. We want something we can actually use: a clearer first draft, less back and forth, and less rework.
Most of the time, when an AI output is not useful, it’s because the request was too open. The tool has to guess what we need: the audience, the purpose, the level of detail, and the format.
So today’s focus is very practical: one repeatable formula that helps us brief the tool better and get stronger outputs from the first attempt.”


Slide 4
“Here is the simple structure I’m proposing: R + T + C + O.
The first element is Role. This tells the AI what perspective or level of expertise it should use. For example, should it respond as a business analyst, a relationship manager, or a senior credit reviewer, ?

The second is Task. This is the specific action we want: summarize, rewrite, compare, or extract. The clearer the verb, the better the output.

The third is Context. This is where we explain the audience, the purpose, what matters, what to include, what to avoid, and any source material the AI should use.

And finally, Output. This defines what ‘done’ looks like: the format, structure, tone, and length.

After using this formula the benefit is simple: less rework, fewer surprises, and more consistent quality.”

Slide 5
“Building on the previous slide, this is the same idea converted into a simple copy-paste template.
The point is not to overcomplicate prompting. It is just to make sure every request gives the AI the minimum information it needs.

The final review line is useful because it asks the AI to flag missing information instead of making assumptions. 

So for recurring tasks, this template can become the starting point.”

Slide 6
